===Etymology===
1830s US, jocular mock-Latin word.<ref name=quinion>{{R:World Wide Words|weirdwords/ww-abs1|Absquatulate|3 Aug. 2002}}</ref> Presumably {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|ab||away (from)|lang=la}} (as in {{term|abscond|lang=en}}) + {{term|squat|lang=en}} + *{{term||-ulate}} (as in {{term|perambulate|lang=en}}, properly {{term|-ate|lang=en}}), hence meaning “get up (from a squat) and depart (quickly)”.<ref name=quinion/><ref>New Orleans ''Weekly Picayune,'' December 1839</ref> Middle portion perhaps influenced by {{term|-le||(frequentive)|lang=en}} and dialectical {{term|squattle||depart|lang=en}}; compare contemporary {{term|skedaddle|lang=en}}.

